{"sections":{"main":{"type":"main-page","disabled":true,"settings":{"padding_top":28,"padding_bottom":28}},"image_banner_nGCfpM":{"type":"image-banner","blocks":{"heading_yrHj8b":{"type":"heading","settings":{"heading":"<strong>Safeguarding Gut Barrier Function<\/strong>","heading_size":"h1"}},"text_enKfTd":{"type":"text","settings":{"texta":"<p>The inside of the gut (the ‘lumen’) is separated from the rest of our body by a single layer of cells called the <strong>intestinal epithelium<\/strong>.<\/p><p>This single layer of cells is so important that the body renews it entirely every 3-5 days in order to remove damaged cells. <a href=\"https:\/\/akkermansia.bravedevelopment.com\/hcp-safeguarding-gut-barrier-function\/?v=d2cb7bbc0d23#references\"><strong>1<\/strong> <\/a>The spaces between the cells are sealed by tight junctions which regulate the permeability of the gut barrier – preventing large molecules from passing through, but allowing in ions, water and small compounds.<\/p><p>However, if the efficiency of the epithelium is compromised, then gut barrier function becomes impaired.<\/p>","text_style":"body"}}},"block_order":["heading_yrHj8b","text_enKfTd"],"settings":{"image":"shopify:\/\/shop_images\/Safeguarding-gut-barrier-health.webp","image_overlay_opacity":30,"image_height":"medium","desktop_content_position":"middle-left","show_text_box":true,"desktop_content_alignment":"left","color_scheme":"scheme-3d94cef0-1db3-4fdd-939f-78dcaaadc830","image_behavior":"fixed","mobile_content_alignment":"center","stack_images_on_mobile":true,"show_text_below":true}},"rich_text_gCprKb":{"type":"rich-text","blocks":{"heading_AdBF8b":{"type":"heading","settings":{"heading":"<strong>Mucus: protecting the gut barrier<\/strong>","heading_size":"h1"}},"text_94FzQm":{"type":"text","settings":{"text":"<p>There is a mucus layer covering the intestinal epithelium, produced by ‘goblet cells’ within the gut barrier. <a href=\"https:\/\/akkermansia.bravedevelopment.com\/hcp-safeguarding-gut-barrier-function\/?v=d2cb7bbc0d23#references\">3<\/a><\/p><p>This mucus layer is crucial in protecting the gut from physical damage and invasion by microorganisms – so if the thickness of the mucus layer decreases, the effectiveness of the gut barrier is compromised. <a href=\"https:\/\/akkermansia.bravedevelopment.com\/hcp-safeguarding-gut-barrier-function\/?v=d2cb7bbc0d23#references\">3<\/a><\/p><p>The mucus layer itself is strengthened by <strong>antimicrobial peptides<\/strong> (AMPs.), which help defend against microorganisms by killing or inhibiting the growth of bacteria close to the epithelium. <a href=\"https:\/\/akkermansia.bravedevelopment.com\/hcp-safeguarding-gut-barrier-function\/?v=d2cb7bbc0d23#references\">3<\/a><\/p>"}}},"block_order":["heading_AdBF8b","text_94FzQm"],"settings":{"desktop_content_position":"center","content_alignment":"center","color_scheme":"","full_width":true,"padding_top":40,"padding_bottom":52}},"image_with_text_home1_GE7WEQ":{"type":"image-with-text-home1","blocks":{"heading_qbygWr":{"type":"heading","settings":{"heading":"<strong>Gut barrier disruption and ‘leaky gut’<\/strong>","heading_size":"h2"}},"text_EJXizq":{"type":"text","settings":{"text":"<p>Cani and Jordan Nature Reviews Gastro & Hepatol 2018<\/p>","text_style":"body"}},"button_wK9HnJ":{"type":"button","settings":{"button_label":"Download this diagram","button_link":"https:\/\/cdn.shopify.com\/s\/files\/1\/0699\/8071\/7276\/files\/Gut-barrier-disruption-diagram.png?v=1723062626","button_style_secondary":false}}},"block_order":["heading_qbygWr","text_EJXizq","button_wK9HnJ"],"settings":{"image":"shopify:\/\/shop_images\/Gut-barrier-disruption-diagram-sm.webp","height":"adapt","desktop_image_width":"large","layout":"text_first","desktop_content_position":"middle","desktop_content_alignment":"left","content_layout":"no-overlap","section_color_scheme":"scheme-2","color_scheme":"scheme-2","image_behavior":"none","mobile_content_alignment":"center","padding_top":36,"padding_bottom":36}},"rich_text_9C8G4X":{"type":"rich-text","blocks":{"text_nPbBcK":{"type":"text","settings":{"text":"<p>The gut barrier manages what comes in and goes out of the gut, and when the function of the gut barrier is disturbed, the gut becomes more permeable – meaning that more components will be able to pass through. <a href=\"https:\/\/akkermansia.bravedevelopment.com\/hcp-safeguarding-gut-barrier-function\/?v=d2cb7bbc0d23#references\">4<\/a><\/p><p>A balanced and diverse gut microbiota is needed for the development, maintenance, and optimal function of the gut barrier, but this composition comes under threat when there are changes in diet, stress, antibiotics or diseases. This leads to a disruption of the gut microbiota composition and functions – a disruption referred to as dysbiosis. <a href=\"https:\/\/akkermansia.bravedevelopment.com\/hcp-safeguarding-gut-barrier-function\/?v=d2cb7bbc0d23#references\">4<\/a><\/p><p>Dysbiosis could allow gut content such as bacterial metabolites and molecules – as well as bacteria themselves – to leak through the gut barrier and into the rest of the body. This increased epithelial permeability is also known as ‘leaky gut’. 4<\/p>"}}},"block_order":["text_nPbBcK"],"settings":{"desktop_content_position":"center","content_alignment":"center","color_scheme":"","full_width":true,"padding_top":40,"padding_bottom":52}},"image_with_text_home1_xfVQRh":{"type":"image-with-text-home1","blocks":{"button_6Wkxhf":{"type":"button","settings":{"button_label":"Download this diagram","button_link":"https:\/\/cdn.shopify.com\/s\/files\/1\/0699\/8071\/7276\/files\/Safeguarding-Gut-Barrier-Function_02.png?v=1723062814","button_style_secondary":false}}},"block_order":["button_6Wkxhf"],"settings":{"image":"shopify:\/\/shop_images\/Safeguarding-Gut-Barrier-Function_02.png","height":"adapt","desktop_image_width":"large","layout":"text_first","desktop_content_position":"middle","desktop_content_alignment":"left","content_layout":"no-overlap","section_color_scheme":"scheme-2","color_scheme":"scheme-2","image_behavior":"none","mobile_content_alignment":"center","padding_top":36,"padding_bottom":36}},"video_wb7KpJ":{"type":"video","settings":{"heading":"<strong>How Akkermansia works<\/strong>","heading_size":"h1","enable_video_looping":true,"video":"shopify:\/\/files\/videos\/The_Akkermansia_Company_16x9_101023_Subtitles.mp4","video_url":"","description":"","full_width":false,"color_scheme":"","padding_top":36,"padding_bottom":36}},"rich_text_UtykLz":{"type":"rich-text","blocks":{"heading_d3Lqba":{"type":"heading","settings":{"heading":"<strong>The wider effectsof ‘leaky gut’<\/strong>","heading_size":"h1"}},"text_FQqRCE":{"type":"text","settings":{"text":"<p>When gut permeability is increased, pro-inflammatory toxins (for example lipopolysaccharides – LPS) can enter the bloodstream. Finally, it leads to chronic low-grade inflammation (a low-level of inflammation but which lasts a long time) throughout the body (e.g. in the liver and adipose tissues).<\/p><p>‘Leaky gut’ is also associated with a variety of gastrointestinal disorders. They include: <\/p>"}}},"block_order":["heading_d3Lqba","text_FQqRCE"],"settings":{"desktop_content_position":"center","content_alignment":"center","color_scheme":"scheme-3d94cef0-1db3-4fdd-939f-78dcaaadc830","full_width":true,"padding_top":40,"padding_bottom":52}},"icon_texst_col_product_pLHQ43":{"type":"icon-texst-col-product","blocks":{"column_qzyfEk":{"type":"column","settings":{"image":"shopify:\/\/shop_images\/Inflammatory-Bowel.svg","title":"<strong>INFLAMMATORY BOWEL DISEASE (IBD)<\/strong>","text":"","link_label":"","link":""}},"column_HrVE6P":{"type":"column","settings":{"image":"shopify:\/\/shop_images\/IBS.svg","title":"<strong>IRRITABLE BOWEL SYNDROME (IBS)<\/strong>","text":"","link_label":"","link":""}},"column_Yz9ePk":{"type":"column","settings":{"image":"shopify:\/\/shop_images\/Coeliac-Disease.svg","title":"<strong>COELIAC DISEASE<\/strong>","text":"","link_label":"","link":""}},"column_etYHtC":{"type":"column","settings":{"image":"shopify:\/\/shop_images\/Colon-Cancer.svg","title":"<strong>EARLY STAGES OF COLON CANCER DEVELOPMENT<\/strong>","text":"","link_label":"","link":""}}},"block_order":["column_qzyfEk","column_HrVE6P","column_Yz9ePk","column_etYHtC"],"settings":{"title":"","heading_size":"h1","image_width":"full","image_ratio":"adapt","columns_desktop":3,"column_alignment":"center","background_style":"none","button_label":"","button_link":"","color_scheme":"scheme-3d94cef0-1db3-4fdd-939f-78dcaaadc830","columns_mobile":"1","swipe_on_mobile":false,"padding_top":36,"padding_bottom":36}},"rich_text_rhWRcU":{"type":"rich-text","blocks":{"text_aqNAxG":{"type":"text","settings":{"text":"<h2>The condition is also associated with numerous extra-intestinal disorders <a href=\"https:\/\/akkermansia.bravedevelopment.com\/hcp-safeguarding-gut-barrier-function\/?v=d2cb7bbc0d23#references\">2 & 3<\/a> such as:<\/h2>"}}},"block_order":["text_aqNAxG"],"settings":{"desktop_content_position":"center","content_alignment":"center","color_scheme":"scheme-3d94cef0-1db3-4fdd-939f-78dcaaadc830","full_width":true,"padding_top":40,"padding_bottom":52}},"icon_texst_col_product_WTBpV4":{"type":"icon-texst-col-product","blocks":{"column_EpYYxD":{"type":"column","settings":{"image":"shopify:\/\/shop_images\/Obesity.svg","title":"<strong>OBESITY<\/strong>","text":"","link_label":"","link":""}},"column_AVbXbz":{"type":"column","settings":{"image":"shopify:\/\/shop_images\/Diabetes.svg","title":"<strong>TYPE-2 AND TYPE-1 DIABETES<\/strong>","text":"","link_label":"","link":""}},"column_HGyNyL":{"type":"column","settings":{"image":"shopify:\/\/shop_images\/Neurological-disorder.svg","title":"<strong>NEUROLOGICAL DISORDERS<\/strong>","text":"","link_label":"","link":""}},"column_8nFXNm":{"type":"column","settings":{"image":"shopify:\/\/shop_images\/Allergies.svg","title":"<strong>FOOD ALLERGY<\/strong>","text":"","link_label":"","link":""}}},"block_order":["column_EpYYxD","column_AVbXbz","column_HGyNyL","column_8nFXNm"],"settings":{"title":"","heading_size":"h1","image_width":"full","image_ratio":"adapt","columns_desktop":3,"column_alignment":"center","background_style":"none","button_label":"","button_link":"","color_scheme":"scheme-3d94cef0-1db3-4fdd-939f-78dcaaadc830","columns_mobile":"1","swipe_on_mobile":false,"padding_top":36,"padding_bottom":36}},"rich_text_EGWfkt":{"type":"rich-text","blocks":{"heading_q3cUk4":{"type":"heading","settings":{"heading":"<strong>How <\/strong><em><strong>Akkermansia muciniphila<\/strong><\/em><strong> can help repair ‘leaky gut’<\/strong>","heading_size":"h1"}},"text_Akfgy7":{"type":"text","settings":{"text":"<p>Because of <em>Akkermansia muciniphila<\/em>’s role in the mucus layer – using mucin as its sole source of nutrients – it also acts to promote mucin production.<\/p><p>By consuming mucin, it stimulates the body to continue mucin production, thereby renewing the mucus layer. Maintaining continual mucus production helps keep the human gut healthy by preventing the invasion of pathogenic bacteria.<\/p><p>Furthermore, as <em>Akkermansia muciniphila<\/em> processes mucin, there are a number of useful byproducts:<\/p>"}}},"block_order":["heading_q3cUk4","text_Akfgy7"],"settings":{"desktop_content_position":"center","content_alignment":"center","color_scheme":"scheme-3d94cef0-1db3-4fdd-939f-78dcaaadc830","full_width":true,"padding_top":40,"padding_bottom":52}},"icon_texst_col_product_R3LzRN":{"type":"icon-texst-col-product","blocks":{"column_tW93Td":{"type":"column","settings":{"image":"shopify:\/\/shop_images\/1-1.webp","title":"<strong>SHORT-CHAIN FATTY ACIDS (E.G. PROPIONATE AND ACETATE)<\/strong>","text":"","link_label":"","link":""}},"column_N3AAQk":{"type":"column","settings":{"image":"shopify:\/\/shop_images\/2-1.webp","title":"<strong>AMINO ACIDS<\/strong>","text":"","link_label":"","link":""}},"column_Hy4WiA":{"type":"column","settings":{"image":"shopify:\/